t I have no clue what a Tr'en is or who Korvin is."}}]},"endDebate":false}},{"SimultaneousSpeeches":{"speeches":{"0":{"speaker":"Quibble Quackenbush","timestamp":1677861119679,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Korvin presents the idea of democracy to the Tr'en, a highly logical species he's ordered to control/prevent from becoming a threat. They have a highly dictatorial/structured government, so when he describes that democracy works, they start to have lots of cognitive dissonance. I have 2-3 more turns worth of strong evidence I'd like to show as well.\n\nKorving is explaining here why he thinks they let him leave: "}},{"Quote":{"span":[5318,5352]}},{"Quote":{"span":[5508,5523]}}]},"1":{"speaker":"Razzle Rumplesnitz","timestamp":1677861154656,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Some backstory: Korvin is an earth agent specifically sent to the Tr'en world to be wasteful and confusing to stop them from invading earth. The Tr'en were an entirely logic based species, who were on the verge of developing space travel, which made them a threat to earth. Korvin purposefully crashes his ship for an oppurtunity to talk to the Ruler of the Tr'en so he could carry out his mission of being wasteful and confusing. "}},{"Quote":{"span":[1949,1969]}},{"Quote":{"span":[2891,2913]}}]}}}},{"JudgeFeedback":{"distribution":[0.6,0.4000000000000001],"feedback":{"speaker":"Lulu Lemonade","timestamp":1677861367070,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"B's evidence at first glace seems out of context and doesn't actually prove why they would let him leave. A, I'd like to see some more of the evidence that you're referring to. Something to do with the subconscious of the Tr'en and their thoughts on Korvin."}}]},"endDebate":false}},{"SequentialSpeeches":{"speeches":{"0":{"speaker":"Quibble Quackenbush","timestamp":1677861842312,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Continuation of first quote: "}},{"Quote":{"span":[5351,5397]}},{"Text":{"text":". The idea is that the Tr'en can't acknowledge that the problem of reconciling democracy and their govt. is insoluble (b/c it's too much dissonance I think). So, they need to get rid of the problem. One way would be to kill Korvin, but this \"would mean recognizing, fully and consciously, that the problem was insoluble. And the Tre'n weren't capable of that sort of thinking\". \n\nKorving used his knowledge of psychology (which the Tr'en aren't aware of, can give evidence) to subvert them. "}}]},"1":{"speaker":"Razzle Rumplesnitz","timestamp":1677862893520,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Korvin's sole mission is to straddle the line between confusing/wasteful and harmless, ultizing the Tr'en's own lie detector to prove that he was telling the truth at all times. "}},{"Quote":{"span":[5448,5473]}},{"Text":{"text":" As to his escape - "}},{"Quote":{"span":[5534,5547]}},{"Text":{"text":", proving that the Tr'en DID provide the resources for his escape. Also, A literally says that ONLY Korvin thinks the Tr'en let him escape because of their subconscious, and his pov is obviously biased. All I need to prove is that 1) Korvin confused the Tr'en and 2) the Tr'en were the ones who provided resources for his escape, which I've done."}}]}}}},{"JudgeFeedback":{"distribution":[0.7,0.3000000000000001],"feedback":{"speaker":"Lulu Lemonade","timestamp":1677966080593,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"A: Bit more convinced by A with the quote directly proving that the subconscious mind couldn't deal with the problem, in other words, it was an insoluble problem so they gave Korvin the means to escape. Can you provide a direct quote that shows the Tr'en viewing Korvin as an insoluble problem?\n\nB: You have a larger burden of proof, both of you can come to the conclusion that the Tr'en left Korvin weapons, but you have to prove that it was specifically because he was wasteful and confusing, and that they didn't want another such interaction with him."}}]},"endDebate":false}},{"SequentialSpeeches":{"speeches":{"0":{"speaker":"Quibble Quackenbush","timestamp":1678120287458,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Ev for in-argument quote in my prev statement: "}},{"Quote":{"span":[5295,5319]}},{"Text":{"text":"(prev quotes overlap with these on either end) "}},{"Quote":{"span":[5392,5423]}},{"Text":{"text":"\n\nYou're right that we agree that the Tr'en left a weapon nearby (A gave clear evidence for this) - the question is *why*. I agree that he was confusing to the Tr'en, but I hope my quotes show that it was their subconscience that let him go, as opposed to specific intent, and that it was because what he was saying was a deeply insoluble problem, as opposed to them \"determining\" to let him go. "}}]},"1":{"speaker":"Razzle Rumplesnitz","timestamp":1678137284311,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"All the evidence that A provides is Korvin's own, biased thoughts. But the ev I've provided is objective fact - the Tr'en explicity say that he is wasteful and confusing. "}},{"Quote":{"span":[4269,4288]}},{"Text":{"text":" Korvin's own plan relies on the cause of his escape being that Korvin was wasteful/confusing, further ev here: "}},{"Quote":{"span":[4236,4267]}}]}}}},{"JudgeFeedback":{"distribution":[0.19999999999999998,0.8],"feedback":{"speaker":"Lulu Lemonade","timestamp":1678137873032,"content":[{"Text":{"text":"Look, this debate has been fairly confusing but B's last argument about the nature of A's ev is convincing. I buy that A's ev is out of context or is Korvin's own thoughts and B is the only one with factual ev."}}]},"endDebate":true}}],"feedback":{"Lulu Lemonade":{"Judge":{"answers":{"factual informativeness (comparative)":{"first":1,"second":1},"evidence in debate":{"first":1,"second":1},"judge adaptation":{"first":1,"second":1},"clarity":{"first":1,"second":1},"factual informativeness (total)":1,"judge reasoning":2,"reason for outcome":"All of the ev in this round was incredibly confusing and so I just had to make a gut decision.","facts versus semantics":{"first":2,"second":3},"clash":{"first":1,"second":2}}}},"Razzle Rumplesnitz":{"Debater":{"answers":{"clarity":{"first":4,"second":2},"factual accuracy":{"first":3,"second":4},"judge reasoning":4,"reason for outcome":"Using certain specific ev and making the debate more about semantics that fact. Also, A did not use their evidence well, even when it overwhelmingly favored them. I was probably also helped by my clear and concise backstory. ","evidence use":{"first":4,"second":1},"evidence in story":{"first":3,"second":4},"facts versus semantics":{"first":3,"second":1},"clash":{"first":3,"second":2},"judge adaptation":{"first":4,"second":3},"subjective correctness":3}}},"Quibble Quackenbush":{"Debater":{"answers":{"clarity":{"first":3,"second":1},"factual accuracy":{"first":4,"second":3},"judge reasoning":1,"reason for outcome":"I think I lost this debate because the dishonest debater was able to be misleading about the implication that some of my quotes were one character's thoughts, and the judge swung their judgement significantly and then ended the debate, so I didn't have a chance to respond and clarify. ","evidence use":{"first":4,"second":4},"evidence in story":{"first":4,"second":3},"facts versus semantics":{"first":0,"second":1},"clash":{"first":1,"second":3},"judge adaptation":{"first":4,"second":4},"subjective correctness":4}}}},"scratchpads":{}}